{"questionId":"35031274","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Texas Star is a Ferris wheel at the state fair in Dallas. The Ferris wheel has a diameter of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>61</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math>. To begin the ride, a passenger gets into a chair at the lowest point on the wheel, which is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext></math> above the ground, as shown in the following diagram. A ride consists of multiple revolutions, and the Ferris wheel makes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math> revolutions per minute.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/56b4b24eb1c57be69d91c620e8c2838d9ead22f1.png\"></p>\n<p>The&nbsp;height of a chair above the ground, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>, measured in metres, during a ride on the Ferris wheel can be modelled by the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo><mi>a</mi><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>b</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>d</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> is the time, in seconds, since a passenger began their ride.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Calculate the value of</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>(period&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>60</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mtext>s</mtext></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow><mn>40</mn></mfrac></math>)</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>9</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong>&nbsp;Accept an answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35031274","referenceCode":"22M.2.SL.TZ2.4a.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"b.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Modelling functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}